SIMPLE: sublime
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sublime
<hw>Sub*lime"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Sublimer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Sublimest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>sublimis</ets>; <ets>sub</ets> under + (perhaps) a word akin to
<ets>limen</ets> lintel, sill, thus meaning, up to the lintel: cf. F.
<ets>sublime</ets>. Cf. <er>Eliminate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Lifted up; high in place; exalted aloft; uplifted; lofty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sublime</qex> on these a tower of steel is reared.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Distinguished by lofty or noble traits; eminent; --
said of persons.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>sublime</xex> Julian
leader.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Awakening or expressing the emotion of awe,
adoration, veneration, heroic resolve, etc.; dignified; grand; solemn;
stately; -- said of an impressive object in nature, of an action, of a
discourse, of a work of art, of a spectacle, etc.; <as>as,
<ex>sublime</ex> scenery; a <ex>sublime</ex> deed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Easy in words thy style, in sense <qex>sublime</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Know how <qex>sublime</qex> a thing it is⟦br⟧
To suffer and be strong.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Elevated by joy; elate.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their hearts were jocund and <qex>sublime</qex>,⟦br⟧
Drunk with idolatry, drunk with wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Lofty of mien; haughty; proud.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Countenance <xex>sublime</xex> and
insolent.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His fair, large front and eye <qex>sublime</qex> declared⟦br⟧
Absolute rule.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Exalted; lofty; noble; majestic. See
<er>Grand</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sublime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sublime
<hw>Sub*lime"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is sublime; -- with
the definite article</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A grand or lofty style
in speaking or writing; a style that expresses lofty
conceptions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>sublime</qex> rises from the nobleness of thoughts, the
magnificence of words, or the harmonious and lively turn of the
phrase.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>That which is grand in nature or art, as
distinguished from the merely beautiful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sublime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sublime
<hw>Sub*lime"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sublimed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Subliming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>sublimare</ets>,
F. <ets>sublimer</ets> to subject to sublimation. See <er>Sublime</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Sublimate</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To raise on high.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A soul <qex>sublimed</qex> by an idea above the region of vanity
and conceit.</q> <rj><qau>E. P. Whipple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To subject to the process of
sublimation; to heat, volatilize, and condense in crystals or powder; to
distill off, and condense in solid form; hence, also, to
purify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To exalt; to heighten; to improve; to
purify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun . . . ⟦br⟧
Which not alone the southern wit <qex>sublimes</qex>,⟦br⟧
But ripens spirits in cold, northern climes.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To dignify; to ennoble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An ordinary gift can not <qex>sublime</qex> a person to a
supernatural employment.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sublime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sublime
<hw>Sub*lime"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>To pass off in vapor, with immediate condensation; specifically, to
evaporate or volatilize from the solid state without apparent melting;
-- said of those substances, like arsenic, benzoic acid, etc., which do
not exhibit a liquid form on heating, except under increased
pressure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sublimed</ent>⟦br⟧
